/* Main computational kernel. The whole function will be timed,
   including the call and return. */
void kernel_syr2k(int n, int m,
                  double alpha,
                  double beta,
                  std::vector<std::vector<double>>& C,
                  std::vector<std::vector<double>>& A,
                  std::vector<std::vector<double>>& B)
{
    // Use OpenMP to parallelise over the outermost loop (rows).
    //       Each thread works on a distinct range of rows, eliminating any
    //       data‑race because every element of C is written only by one
    //       thread.  The schedule is static to keep the partitioning fixed.
#pragma omp parallel for schedule(static)
    for (int i = 0; i < n; ++i)
    {
        // Alias the row pointers for a small speed gain.
        double* restrict Ci = C[i].data();   // row i of C
        double* restrict Ai = A[i].data();   // row i of A
        double* restrict Bi = B[i].data();   // row i of B

        for (int j = 0; j <= i; ++j)
        {
            // Start from the scaled value of C[i][j]
            double sum = Ci[j] * beta;

            // Accumulate the rank‑2 update for this column
            //   C[i][j] += alpha * (A[j][k] * B[i][k] + B[j][k] * A[i][k])
            //   for all k.
            const double* restrict Aj = A[j].data(); // row j of A
            const double* restrict Bj = B[j].data(); // row j of B

            for (int k = 0; k < m; ++k)
            {
                sum += alpha * (Aj[k] * Bi[k] + Bj[k] * Ai[k]);
            }

            Ci[j] = sum;
        }
    }
}
```
This replacement keeps the exact semantics of the original function while:

* Removing the nested `j`/`k` loops over the full `C[i][j]` matrix and instead working only on the lower triangular part.
* Using pointer aliases (`restrict`) to aid the compiler's optimization.
* Parallelising the outermost loop with OpenMP, making efficient use of the 8 available threads on an x86‑64 machine.
* Falling back to simple arithmetic loops (no additional context or blocking) so the code remains clear and well‑behaved for all input sizes.

